                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d574">
                <head>574. Telegram 327 to Prague<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d574fn1">Source:
                        Department of State, Central Files, 611.93/4–956. Confidential; Limit
                        Distribution. Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_MWP_1">McConaughy</persName>;
                        cleared by Sebald, <persName corresp="#p_RWS_1">Robertson</persName>,
                        Phleger, Donovan (EE), Chase (SCA), McIlvaine (P) and Macomber (S).</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1956-04-12">April 12, 1956, 9:22 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <pb facs="d574-1" n="1" type="facsimile" xml:id="d574-1"/>
                <p>327. For <persName corresp="#p_JUA_1">Johnson</persName>.</p>
                <p>Geneva’s 1739. Close check through Department shows that no repeat no change in
                    Department’s position on passports valid for Communist China has taken place.
                    Policy not to reexamine question prior to release of imprisoned Americans
                    remains unaltered. Department unable to find any indication of recent approach
                    by Catledge or any other New York Times representative on this subject.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF_1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
